I got two handguns,

260
00:12:24,526 --> 00:12:26,360
one automatic.

261
00:12:29,739 --> 00:12:32,234
(engine roaring,
tires screeching)

262
00:12:38,333 --> 00:12:39,495
We gotta get out of here.

263
00:12:39,625 --> 00:12:40,788
I'm gonna take
the automatic.

264
00:12:40,877 --> 00:12:43,120
You sure about this?

265
00:12:55,141 --> 00:12:57,134
(gunfire continues)

266
00:13:04,485 --> 00:13:05,975
You ready?

267
00:13:06,069 --> 00:13:07,482
Move.

268
00:13:13,327 --> 00:13:15,696
♪♪

269
00:13:25,464 --> 00:13:28,380
♪♪

270
00:13:28,509 --> 00:13:29,797
(grunting)

271
00:13:37,435 --> 00:13:38,926
(grunts)

272
00:13:47,570 --> 00:13:49,188
Lewis?

273
00:13:49,281 --> 00:13:50,899
Lewis!

274
00:13:52,910 --> 00:13:54,743
Officer down!

275
00:13:54,869 --> 00:13:57,238
Officer down-- 331 Hamilton.

276
00:13:57,372 --> 00:13:58,739
This is Detective Alex Murphy

277
00:13:58,874 --> 00:14:00,742
in need
of immediate medical assistance.

278
00:14:00,876 --> 00:14:03,712
331 Hamilton Road.

279
00:14:03,879 --> 00:14:05,747
Jack.

280
00:14:05,881 --> 00:14:06,747
Jack, come on.

281
00:14:06,840 --> 00:14:09,255
Jack, can you hear me?

282
00:14:09,385 --> 00:14:11,002
Jack, stay with me.

283
00:14:11,136 --> 00:14:12,252
(thunder rumbles)

284
00:14:12,387 --> 00:14:14,131
Jack.

285
00:14:14,265 --> 00:14:16,053
KAREN (voice-over): Alex, you
don't do something like this...

286
00:14:16,142 --> 00:14:17,554
- Come on, Jack!
-...unless you bring it

287
00:14:17,685 --> 00:14:19,177
to me first.

288
00:14:19,270 --> 00:14:20,853
Vallon's connected.

289
00:14:20,938 --> 00:14:22,932
I'm warning you, don't
make any more moves

290
00:14:23,066 --> 00:14:24,228
until I vet this.

291
00:14:24,358 --> 00:14:25,724
If officers are supplying him
with guns...

292
00:14:25,818 --> 00:14:28,734
That's up to IAD.

293
00:14:28,821 --> 00:14:30,939
I'll handle it.

294
00:14:36,287 --> 00:14:38,121
MAN (voice-over):
I don't care how sophisticated

295
00:14:38,289 --> 00:14:41,000
these machines are,
Mr. Sellars.

296
00:14:41,125 --> 00:14:45,749
A machine does not know
what it feels like to be human.

297
00:14:45,839 --> 00:14:48,630
It can't understand
the value of human life.

298
00:14:48,758 --> 00:14:51,093
Why should it be
allowed to take one?

299
00:14:51,178 --> 00:14:54,343
To, to, to legislate
over life and death,

300
00:14:54,473 --> 00:14:58,516
we need people who understand
right from wrong.

301
00:14:58,643 --> 00:14:59,805
What do your machines feel?

302
00:14:59,936 --> 00:15:02,647
Well, uh, they feel no anger.

303
00:15:02,732 --> 00:15:04,474
They feel no prejudice.

304
00:15:04,566 --> 00:15:06,275
They feel no fatigue,

305
00:15:06,401 --> 00:15:09,317
which makes them ideal
for law enforcement.

306
00:15:09,404 --> 00:15:13,357
Putting these machines
on the streets

307
00:15:13,493 --> 00:15:16,534
will save
countless American lives.

308
00:15:16,662 --> 00:15:18,153
- You're evading the question.
- No, I'm not.

309
00:15:18,289 --> 00:15:19,826
Yes, you're evading
the question.

310
00:15:19,915 --> 00:15:22,956
I asked, what do
these machines feel?

311
00:15:23,085 --> 00:15:26,377
If one of them...
killed a child,

312
00:15:26,506 --> 00:15:28,876
what would it feel?

313
00:15:32,303 --> 00:15:34,171
- Nothing.
- And that's the problem.

314
00:15:34,305 --> 00:15:37,847
That's why 72% of Americans
will not stand

315
00:15:37,976 --> 00:15:39,889
for a robot
pulling the trigger.

316
00:15:40,020 --> 00:15:42,013
(applause)

317
00:15:47,611 --> 00:15:49,022
MAN (voice-over): The world's
most valuable market,

318
00:15:49,154 --> 00:15:50,988
and we can't touch it.

319
00:15:51,072 --> 00:15:52,690
With a domestic expansion,

320
00:15:52,783 --> 00:15:56,405
we'd clear $600 billion
per annum.

321
00:15:56,537 --> 00:15:59,247
In other words, every second
that law is in existence,

322
00:15:59,372 --> 00:16:00,364
we are hemorrhaging money.

323
00:16:00,499 --> 00:16:02,242
What do you
want me to do?

324
00:16:02,376 --> 00:16:04,415
We've thrown cash at senators
at both sides of the aisle.

325
00:16:04,545 --> 00:16:06,083
Nobody's budging.

326
00:16:06,213 --> 00:16:08,047
They don't want to vote
against their constituents,

327
00:16:08,174 --> 00:16:11,249
so, unless we sway public
opinion, the battle's lost.

328
00:16:11,385 --> 00:16:14,882
Now, to that effect,
my team have come up

329
00:16:14,972 --> 00:16:17,762
with a pretty aggressive
new campaign.

330
00:16:17,892 --> 00:16:20,557
Wow factor
off the charts.

331
00:16:20,687 --> 00:16:23,887
We need to give Americans
a product they can love,

332
00:16:23,981 --> 00:16:25,518
a figure they can
rally behind.

333
00:16:25,650 --> 00:16:26,891
Sir, I have dissected
this bill.

334
00:16:26,984 --> 00:16:28,272
There are no loopholes.

335
00:16:28,403 --> 00:16:30,520
We can't put a machine
on the streets.

336
00:16:30,612 --> 00:16:31,945
Forget machines.

337
00:16:32,073 --> 00:16:33,862
You saw the polls.

338
00:16:33,951 --> 00:16:37,197
Americans don't want a machine.

339
00:16:37,287 --> 00:16:42,366
They want a product
with a conscience.

340
00:16:42,459 --> 00:16:46,628
They want something
that knows...

341
00:16:48,381 --> 00:16:52,505
...what it feels like
to be human.

342
00:16:58,891 --> 00:17:01,557
We're gonna put a man
inside a machine.

343
00:17:04,022 --> 00:17:05,935
DOCTOR (voice-over):
You're not you

344
00:17:06,024 --> 00:17:08,769
because of your legs,
your arms, your hands.

345
00:17:08,902 --> 00:17:10,611
You're you
because of your brain.

346
00:17:10,739 --> 00:17:13,608
It's your, your brain's capacity
to process information

347
00:17:13,699 --> 00:17:15,534
that makes you who you are.

348
00:17:16,452 --> 00:17:17,944
Relax and just do

349
00:17:18,037 --> 00:17:20,030
what you've always done.

350
00:17:24,543 --> 00:17:26,627
I've never played with these.

351
00:17:26,712 --> 00:17:29,127
The music doesn't come
from your fingers, Michael,

352
00:17:29,298 --> 00:17:30,961
it comes from your mind.

353
00:17:31,092 --> 00:17:33,177
All you have to do
is let it out.

354
00:17:33,303 --> 00:17:36,138
Please.

355
00:17:47,234 --> 00:17:49,227
♪♪

356
00:18:01,081 --> 00:18:03,074
- ♪♪
-(gentle laugh)

357
00:18:06,086 --> 00:18:07,670
(voice breaking):
Oh, my God.

358
00:18:07,797 --> 00:18:09,335
(laughs quietly)

359
00:18:09,465 --> 00:18:10,331
(stumbles over chords)

360
00:18:10,466 --> 00:18:11,331
(groans in frustration)

361
00:18:11,467 --> 00:18:13,550
No, it's okay. Easy.

362
00:18:15,596 --> 00:18:17,088
His emotions are peaking.

363
00:18:17,223 --> 00:18:18,213
The readings are
getting clouded.

364
00:18:18,349 --> 00:18:19,637
NORTON:
It's okay.

365
00:18:19,726 --> 00:18:21,058
Relax.

366
00:18:21,186 --> 00:18:23,225
If you get too emotional,
it'll change

367
00:18:23,354 --> 00:18:24,516
the chemistry in your brain.

368
00:18:24,605 --> 00:18:26,598
It'll throw the system out.

369
00:18:29,110 --> 00:18:31,023
You're doing great.

370
00:18:31,112 --> 00:18:33,105
Come on.

371
00:18:34,449 --> 00:18:36,442
♪♪

372
00:18:43,167 --> 00:18:44,158
(fumbling)

373
00:18:45,877 --> 00:18:49,203
I need emotion to play.

374
00:18:49,298 --> 00:18:51,667
SELLARS: "Concierto de
Aranjuez," second movement.

375
00:18:51,758 --> 00:18:54,549
Beautiful piece.

376
00:18:54,636 --> 00:18:56,003
Dennett, when you have a moment.

377
00:18:56,097 --> 00:18:57,384
Thank you.

378
00:18:57,473 --> 00:18:58,886
NORTON (voice-over):
We agreed on this

379
00:18:58,975 --> 00:19:00,558
along time ago, Raymond.

380
00:19:00,684 --> 00:19:04,261
I, I, I wouldn't be asked to
develop combat applications.

381
00:19:04,396 --> 00:19:06,766
My, my work here is driven

382
00:19:06,899 --> 00:19:07,890
by its own questions.

383
00:19:07,984 --> 00:19:09,100
And your work is brilliant,

384
00:19:09,235 --> 00:19:11,228
but your ideas
are being underutilized.

385
00:19:11,321 --> 00:19:14,065
Look, I think I found a way

386
00:19:14,156 --> 00:19:18,404
to put real revenue stream
behind your research and save

387
00:19:18,494 --> 00:19:22,037
thousands of lives
in the process.

388
00:19:28,004 --> 00:19:30,044
(tires screech)

389
00:19:34,469 --> 00:19:35,802
You're not keeping
up your end,

390
00:19:35,929 --> 00:19:37,386
leaving me exposed
like that.

391
00:19:37,555 --> 00:19:38,922
Detective Murphy's just
a little impulsive.

392
00:19:39,057 --> 00:19:40,220
So put him on
the payroll.

393
00:19:40,309 --> 00:19:41,765
Why are we talking
about this?

394
00:19:41,893 --> 00:19:43,135
It won't work, and now
that his partner got hit,

395
00:19:43,270 --> 00:19:44,136
he's never gonna let it go.

396
00:19:44,271 --> 00:19:46,264
What is that?

397
00:19:46,356 --> 00:19:47,598
Lewis's hospital.

398
00:19:47,691 --> 00:19:49,057
Alex is dropping
by this afternoon,

399
00:19:49,151 --> 00:19:51,190
in case you want
to send flowers.

400
00:19:53,614 --> 00:19:55,105
(scoffs)

401
00:19:55,198 --> 00:19:56,064
Yeah.

402
00:19:56,158 --> 00:19:57,446
I kill a cop,

403
00:19:57,535 --> 00:19:59,778
looking over my shoulder
the rest of my life.

404
00:19:59,912 --> 00:20:01,279
That's not good for business.

405
00:20:01,372 --> 00:20:04,788
Who do you think's
gonna be investigating you?

406
00:20:10,213 --> 00:20:13,289
I'm gonna go hard
after Lake and Daniels.

407
00:20:14,928 --> 00:20:17,969
Gonna have 'em in bracelets
within a month, man.

408
00:20:18,056 --> 00:20:21,097
Hey, Vallon,
I'm walking up right now.

409
00:20:21,184 --> 00:20:23,268
Cameras off?

410
00:20:25,271 --> 00:20:26,810
Clear.

411
00:20:26,899 --> 00:20:27,934
MURPHY (voice-over):
You were right.

412
00:20:28,024 --> 00:20:30,860
We should've had backup.

413
00:20:30,985 --> 00:20:32,523
I'm sorry.

414
00:20:34,740 --> 00:20:37,530
You're not really
sleeping, are you?

415
00:20:37,659 --> 00:20:40,154
(both chuckle)

416
00:20:40,245 --> 00:20:42,705
Asshole.

417
00:20:43,748 --> 00:20:45,992
Sergeant Thomas Fry, NYPD.

418
00:20:46,126 --> 00:20:48,996
Paralyzed from the waist down.

419
00:20:49,088 --> 00:20:53,131
He has let himself go
a little since the accident.

420
00:20:53,217 --> 00:20:54,333
Pass.

421
00:20:54,426 --> 00:20:56,135
Yeah, yeah, fair enough.

422
00:20:56,220 --> 00:20:58,464
Officer Alfred Miller, Denver.

423
00:20:58,556 --> 00:21:02,850
Severe cere-- cerebellar...

424
00:21:02,978 --> 00:21:04,561
Cerebellar ataxia.

425
00:21:04,687 --> 00:21:06,179
That's why you're
the doctor, Doctor.

426
00:21:06,314 --> 00:21:08,353
He scored
through the roof

427
00:21:08,483 --> 00:21:10,522
with our urban demos.

428
00:21:10,610 --> 00:21:12,148
Let's keep this one in mind;
I like this guy.

429
00:21:12,237 --> 00:21:13,320
Very good, sir,
I saved

430
00:21:13,489 --> 00:21:16,404
the best for last.

431
00:21:16,532 --> 00:21:19,823
I give you Sergeant Jack
Freeman, masculinity incarnate.

432
00:21:19,910 --> 00:21:22,827
Led Pittsburgh SWAT
for five years,

433
00:21:22,914 --> 00:21:25,408
now confined to a wheelchair.

434
00:21:25,541 --> 00:21:29,744
I... think I can
see the appeal.

435
00:21:29,880 --> 00:21:31,042
NORTON:
No.

436
00:21:31,131 --> 00:21:32,498
What? Why?

437
00:21:32,591 --> 00:21:33,581
Well, check
the psych evaluation.

438
00:21:33,716 --> 00:21:36,086
He's far too unstable.

439
00:21:36,219 --> 00:21:38,053
He's trying to say
that he has a temper.

440
00:21:38,138 --> 00:21:40,348
Have you any idea what we'd
be putting him through?

441
00:21:40,432 --> 00:21:42,391
The psychological
strain requires

442
00:21:42,476 --> 00:21:44,059
someone emotionally
balanced.

443
00:21:44,145 --> 00:21:46,229
We have to be scientific.

444
00:21:46,313 --> 00:21:48,727
I mean, we're not selling
a soft drink here, are we?

445
00:21:48,857 --> 00:21:50,020
He's right.

446
00:21:50,109 --> 00:21:52,854
Okay, keep looking.

447
00:21:52,945 --> 00:21:55,406
WOMAN:
David, what did I say?

448
00:21:55,490 --> 00:21:56,571
Not until
you're finished.

449
00:21:56,657 --> 00:21:57,569
Hey, guys.

450
00:21:57,659 --> 00:21:59,276
Hi, Dad.

451
00:21:59,410 --> 00:22:01,028
Hey.

452
00:22:01,120 --> 00:22:02,111
Hey, little monkey.

453
00:22:06,125 --> 00:22:07,538
How's the game, buddy?

454
00:22:07,669 --> 00:22:10,630
Damon got ejected, but we
got a two-man advantage.

455
00:22:10,755 --> 00:22:12,087
Oh, yeah?

456
00:22:12,173 --> 00:22:13,586
- That's fantastic.
- Hey, D,

457
00:22:13,675 --> 00:22:15,259
why don't you
head upstairs,

458
00:22:15,343 --> 00:22:17,210
start getting ready for bed?

459
00:22:17,304 --> 00:22:19,092
But he just got home.

460
00:22:19,222 --> 00:22:21,090
I'll be up in a second.

461
00:22:21,224 --> 00:22:22,260
Tuck you in, okay?

462
00:22:22,392 --> 00:22:23,429
All right?

463
00:22:23,519 --> 00:22:26,890
(Alex grunts)

464
00:22:26,980 --> 00:22:28,143
Now give your mom
a kiss.

465
00:22:28,274 --> 00:22:29,139
Good night, baby.

466
00:22:29,274 --> 00:22:31,268
Too slow, boy.

467
00:22:32,445 --> 00:22:35,030
You're just too slow.

468
00:22:41,329 --> 00:22:43,241
How's Jack holding up?

469
00:22:43,330 --> 00:22:45,791
They said a week
till he's back on his feet.

470
00:22:45,874 --> 00:22:46,786
It's my fault.

471
00:22:46,876 --> 00:22:47,786
He shouldn't even

472
00:22:47,876 --> 00:22:49,916
have been there.

473
00:22:50,004 --> 00:22:52,839
Here.

474
00:22:55,885 --> 00:22:57,877
(sighs)

475
00:23:11,234 --> 00:23:13,228
(kisses gently)

476
00:23:44,769 --> 00:23:46,762
(both panting)

477
00:23:52,777 --> 00:23:55,647
(both moaning quietly)

478
00:23:55,738 --> 00:23:56,901
(car alarm blaring
in distance)

479
00:23:57,032 --> 00:23:59,071
Oh, shit, I thought
I fixed that.

480
00:23:59,200 --> 00:24:00,862
It'll stop.

481
00:24:00,994 --> 00:24:03,533
(alarm continues)

482
00:24:03,621 --> 00:24:06,332
(moans)

483
00:24:06,416 --> 00:24:07,907
It's gonna wake up David.

484
00:24:08,043 --> 00:24:10,036
(alarm continues)

485
00:24:16,842 --> 00:24:19,680
(remote chirps,
alarm continues blaring)

486
00:24:19,764 --> 00:24:21,755
(alarm continues)

487
00:24:27,897 --> 00:24:29,890
(remote chirps,
alarm continues blaring)

488
00:24:32,819 --> 00:24:34,811
(remote chirps,
alarm continues blaring)

489
00:24:43,038 --> 00:24:46,032
♪♪

490
00:24:51,921 --> 00:24:54,460
NORTON (voice-over):
He suffered fourth-degree burns

491
00:24:54,591 --> 00:24:56,584
over 80% of his body.

492
00:24:56,718 --> 00:24:59,964
Lower spine has been severed.

493
00:25:00,096 --> 00:25:03,764
If he survives,
he'll be paralyzed

494
00:25:03,934 --> 00:25:07,350
from the waist down
and confined to a wheelchair.

495
00:25:09,773 --> 00:25:13,143
Mrs. Murphy...

496
00:25:13,276 --> 00:25:17,103
we, we don't have
to do this.

497
00:25:17,239 --> 00:25:19,984
I need to know everything
before I make a decision.

498
00:25:21,243 --> 00:25:23,111
(Clara sighs)

499
00:25:23,203 --> 00:25:24,947
Please continue.

500
00:25:25,039 --> 00:25:27,829
Vestibulocochlear,

501
00:25:27,958 --> 00:25:32,001
optical nerves
have been critically damaged.

502
00:25:32,130 --> 00:25:34,750
He'll be blind in one eye,

503
00:25:34,841 --> 00:25:37,301
most likely deaf.

504
00:25:37,385 --> 00:25:39,003
Frankly, Dr. Norton
and the Omni Foundation

505
00:25:39,137 --> 00:25:40,628
are the leaders
in this field.

506
00:25:40,721 --> 00:25:44,970
In my opinion, this is the only
chance your husband has.

507
00:25:45,059 --> 00:25:47,519
I'd seriously consider
their offer.

508
00:25:49,730 --> 00:25:51,643
I'm sorry, Doctor.

509
00:25:51,733 --> 00:25:54,523
I need time to think.

510
00:25:54,652 --> 00:25:55,860
LIZ: I'm afraid,
Mrs. Murphy,

511
00:25:55,987 --> 00:25:58,732
time is one thing
you don't have.

512
00:26:01,743 --> 00:26:03,827
You say you
can save him,

513
00:26:03,953 --> 00:26:05,947
but what does that mean?

514
00:26:08,750 --> 00:26:11,997
What kind of life will he have?

515
00:26:20,429 --> 00:26:23,174
♪ Fly me to the moon ♪

516
00:26:23,265 --> 00:26:27,012
♪ Let me play
among the stars... ♪

517
00:26:27,102 --> 00:26:28,844
Thanks.

518
00:26:28,937 --> 00:26:30,180
Thanks, buddy.

519
00:26:30,315 --> 00:26:32,023
You know she's gonna
make me dance again.

520
00:26:32,107 --> 00:26:33,725
Now, that
I've got to see.

521
00:26:33,859 --> 00:26:35,022
You don't want
to see that.

522
00:26:35,111 --> 00:26:36,898
Here she comes now.

523
00:26:37,029 --> 00:26:38,065
Hold on to that.

524
00:26:38,197 --> 00:26:39,313
Get out there, partner.

525
00:26:39,407 --> 00:26:40,489
♪ Hold my hand... ♪

526
00:26:40,575 --> 00:26:42,944
Every time.

